This PR defines Ext-types in general abelian categories by shrinking types of morphisms in the derived category. The abelian group structure shall be defined in a future PR.

(When this API is developed further, it shall replace the current definition which applies only to categories with enough projectives.)

I'm a bit confused. How can Lean find the right `w'` to get a `HasDerivedCategory.{w'} C` instance?
Or does Lean ignore the universe parameter and use the first `HasDerivedCategory.{*} C`? Do we need compatibility lemmas for multiple `HasDerivedCategory.{*} C` instances?

The idea is that the definition of `Ext` groups does not depend on any `HasDerivedCategory` variable. For the definition of the abelian group structure, the best solution I have found is to define it using the constructed derived category. Then, using #14153 and some more (painful) work (wip PR #13989), I shall show that the abelian group structure is compatible with any `HasDerivedCategory` variable. At the same time, we shall also see that an exact functor induces maps on `Ext`-groups that are compatible with `Functor.mapDerivedCategory`. (By design, I believe we should not define any global instance of `HasDerivedCategory`. It is like with `Category` for which the universe is determined by the first (and hopefully unique) variable found.)

By "constructed derived category", do you mean the "formally invert all arrows" large universe construction?
I think it would be nicer to specify which `HasDerivedCategory` is used explicitly here rather than relying on the belief that "we should not define any global instance of `HasDerivedCategory`" in order to avoid nasty diamonds, but I IIRC we don't have that construction in mathlib yet right?

Yes, the "constructed derived category" is the large universe construction (this is the target category of `MorphismProperty.Q`), which is already used *internally* in order to define `Ext`. This is the same localized category that is provided by `HasDerivedCategory.standard`.

Providing global instances of `HasDerivedCategory` for general categories is a very bad idea, because it would mean that we would basically have to specify the universes everywhere when we use the `DerivedCategory` API...

The only other reasonable approach I see would be to define the `Add` instance on the `Ext` types using suitable binary biproducts and the basic functoriality of `Ext`. I have just removed the `AddCommGroup` instance, and we shall see the details in future PRs.
Ah sorry I think I misread the original approach (I thought it took a `[HasDerivedCategory.{w} C]` instance variable) and that approach is perfectly fine IMO.
The other approach I am suggesting just above might be slightly more convenient, I will experiment a little bit with it. The better is to keep the `AddCommGroup` instance out of this PR.
